WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.920
Alright, thank you everyone for being here, and bless you for choosing to come to a talk

00:00:12.920 --> 00:00:15.760
about boxplots.

00:00:15.760 --> 00:00:21.139
And so I'd like to tell you a story about a bug in ggplot2's boxplots, but this talk

00:00:21.139 --> 00:00:26.080
is not really about boxplots, because it's really about how to go about understanding

00:00:26.080 --> 00:00:30.200
and fixing bugs when you're faced with a problem that you don't know how to solve.

00:00:30.200 --> 00:00:33.759
And so I'm hoping that the strategy that I'll share that helped me solve this particular

00:00:33.759 --> 00:00:39.419
bug will be one that you can take and maybe use in your own coding work, whether that's

00:00:39.419 --> 00:00:43.900
working on R packages, or data analysis code, or any other situation that you might find

00:00:43.900 --> 00:00:46.860
yourself in.

00:00:46.860 --> 00:00:52.040
So a while back, someone opened this issue on the GitHub repo for ggplot2.

00:00:52.040 --> 00:00:58.119
They said, when I try to produce boxplots with colors depending on a categorical variable,

00:00:58.119 --> 00:01:01.900
these appear overlapping if var width is set to true.

00:01:01.900 --> 00:01:06.820
So if you're not familiar with boxplots in ggplot, var width is an option that lets the

00:01:06.820 --> 00:01:11.900
boxes vary in width depending on the number of points they represent, which can be really

00:01:11.900 --> 00:01:17.459
useful if you have very imbalanced classes in your data that you want to represent that

00:01:17.459 --> 00:01:24.239
some of these boxes are representing fewer points than others.

00:01:24.239 --> 00:01:29.120
So I was working as a ggplot2 intern at the time, and I was mainly supposed to be focusing

00:01:29.120 --> 00:01:33.959
on other aspects of the code base, but I saw this issue come in, and I thought, this should

00:01:33.959 --> 00:01:35.120
be straightforward to fix.

00:01:35.120 --> 00:01:39.879
Like, I'll just knock this one out really quick.

00:01:39.879 --> 00:01:43.959
But we've got about 18 minutes of this talk slot left, so you can probably guess that

00:01:43.959 --> 00:01:46.239
that isn't how things actually turned out.

00:01:46.260 --> 00:01:51.019
In fact, it was a way more complicated bug than I had really anticipated, and I ended

00:01:51.019 --> 00:01:57.580
up having to write an entirely new algorithm to place boxes in boxplots, and working on

00:01:57.580 --> 00:02:01.739
this was probably the deepest that I had ever gone into trying to fix just one seemingly

00:02:01.739 --> 00:02:07.699
simple bug, and I learned a lot about how to approach this process in doing so.

00:02:07.699 --> 00:02:13.020
So when I'm trying to fix a bug in some code, I like to let myself be guided by three questions.

00:02:13.020 --> 00:02:16.059
How do I know what the bug is first?

00:02:16.059 --> 00:02:18.199
And then how do I fix it?

00:02:18.199 --> 00:02:21.279
And then how do I know when I'm done fixing it?

00:02:21.279 --> 00:02:26.639
And by answering these questions, I find I can keep myself a little bit on track and

00:02:26.639 --> 00:02:31.479
that there are some specific strategies that I can use in answering each.

00:02:31.479 --> 00:02:36.279
So before you can go about fixing a bug, you have to know what the bug is, and the best

00:02:36.279 --> 00:02:40.279
way to figure that out is to start by isolating the problem.

00:02:40.279 --> 00:02:44.119
So at this point, you're not necessarily even trying to think about what the cause of the

00:02:44.139 --> 00:02:48.619
problem is, but rather just trying to pin down exactly when it happens.

00:02:48.619 --> 00:02:54.460
And the best way to convey this is through a minimal reproducible example or a reprex.

00:02:54.460 --> 00:02:59.300
A reprex should be the minimal code and data necessary to produce the problem that you're

00:02:59.300 --> 00:03:00.580
seeing.

00:03:00.580 --> 00:03:05.259
And the minimal part is really important here, because if you have thousands of rows of data

00:03:05.259 --> 00:03:09.619
and lots of custom plot themes, there's a lot of distractions and it's hard to tell

00:03:09.619 --> 00:03:12.679
what's really relevant to the problem at hand.

00:03:12.679 --> 00:03:19.419
So paring it down can really help isolate the problem and often can turn up, can help

00:03:19.419 --> 00:03:23.320
you figure out what is causing it through that process.

00:03:23.320 --> 00:03:29.380
Then the reproducible part is important so that you or someone else can know if you fixed

00:03:29.380 --> 00:03:30.380
it.

00:03:30.380 --> 00:03:33.720
If you're not sure when the problem occurs, you can't make it happen reliably, it's hard

00:03:33.720 --> 00:03:36.919
to know if it's really been solved.

00:03:36.919 --> 00:03:42.380
So the reprex package by Jenny Bryan makes it really easy to produce these nice standalone

00:03:42.380 --> 00:03:48.500
copy-pasteable reprexes and it can even do things like embed figures into the output.

00:03:48.500 --> 00:03:53.279
And fortunately, the person who reported this issue provided a reprex of their problem,

00:03:53.279 --> 00:03:56.380
so they did this step for me of isolating the problem.

00:03:56.380 --> 00:04:01.440
So without any extraneous detail, they identified exactly when the problem occurs.

00:04:01.440 --> 00:04:04.839
When boxes have variable widths, they overlap.

00:04:04.839 --> 00:04:07.520
If they don't have variable widths, they don't.

00:04:07.520 --> 00:04:12.080
And I really like this reprex because every piece of code that is in it is necessary to

00:04:12.779 --> 00:04:14.339
producing this problem.

00:04:14.339 --> 00:04:18.299
They also gave an example of the case where the problem doesn't occur.

00:04:18.299 --> 00:04:23.260
When we have these uniform width boxes, you can see that they get moved side to side and

00:04:23.260 --> 00:04:24.260
they don't overlap.

00:04:24.260 --> 00:04:28.140
So that's what we're aiming for.

00:04:28.140 --> 00:04:33.140
So once you've isolated when the problem occurs, it's time to start digging into the cause.

00:04:33.140 --> 00:04:37.380
And to do that, you need to kind of follow the data through its journey to the point

00:04:37.380 --> 00:04:39.859
where the problem occurs.

00:04:39.859 --> 00:04:44.000
If plotting code in particular, this can be sort of challenging because a lot is going

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:50.320
on within ggplot2 to turn a data frame that you provide into a plot.

00:04:50.320 --> 00:04:54.119
And at the time that I worked on this, I was not familiar with all of the steps that were

00:04:54.119 --> 00:04:59.239
happening, so I wasn't even sure really where to start looking.

00:04:59.239 --> 00:05:01.119
But this was sort of my thought process.

00:05:01.119 --> 00:05:05.320
So looking at the code that was reported, I can see that in the buggy version of the

00:05:05.320 --> 00:05:07.839
plot, we get this warning message.

00:05:07.839 --> 00:05:11.739
Warning, position dodge requires non-overlapping X intervals.

00:05:11.739 --> 00:05:15.700
And this is a little bit confusing to me because, like, yeah, the whole point is that these

00:05:15.700 --> 00:05:17.420
are overlapping and we don't want them to.

00:05:17.420 --> 00:05:20.579
Like, we're not trying to have overlapping X intervals here.

00:05:20.579 --> 00:05:27.940
But I can latch on to this position dodge and sort of try to figure out what is happening

00:05:27.940 --> 00:05:32.299
around there that is probably contributing to this problem, since that's in the warning

00:05:32.299 --> 00:05:35.420
message.

00:05:35.420 --> 00:05:39.239
So I'm going to try to find position dodge and see if I can figure out what it's meant

00:05:39.239 --> 00:05:40.399
to do.

00:05:40.399 --> 00:05:45.760
And to do this, I need to search into the ggplot2 code base, which I have a copy of

00:05:45.760 --> 00:05:46.760
locally.

00:05:46.760 --> 00:05:49.640
I could search within the folder of code and find it.

00:05:49.640 --> 00:05:55.040
But honestly, a lot of the time, I'm searching on GitHub, and so I'll type in position dodge

00:05:55.040 --> 00:06:02.019
and find where it's located and see where I go from there.

00:06:02.019 --> 00:06:08.260
So then I go through the function, reading it line by line, and seeing when the function

00:06:08.260 --> 00:06:12.059
that I'm on may be calling some other function that I don't know, and sort of repeating that

00:06:12.059 --> 00:06:16.279
process of just reading the code, reading the comments, hoping that I can make some

00:06:16.279 --> 00:06:18.359
sense of it.

00:06:18.359 --> 00:06:21.799
Hopefully the comments in code are clear enough that it's possible to do this.

00:06:21.799 --> 00:06:27.160
And in this case, I was able to figure out just by reading that there's sort of this

00:06:27.160 --> 00:06:33.480
pathway that the data goes through from position dodge to capital P position dodge to a function

00:06:33.480 --> 00:06:36.679
called collide and then posdodge.

00:06:36.679 --> 00:06:42.440
And it appeared that those last two were the ones kind of controlling the most about how

00:06:42.440 --> 00:06:46.399
these boxes were being placed.

00:06:46.399 --> 00:06:52.440
So at a high level, what collide does is that it gets information about the boxes before

00:06:52.440 --> 00:06:54.420
they've been moved side to side.

00:06:54.420 --> 00:07:00.660
So when you have these overlap, it gets these overlapping boxes, looks for the overlap,

00:07:00.660 --> 00:07:08.160
and then sends all of the overlapping boxes to posdodge, which will shrink them down and

00:07:08.160 --> 00:07:09.500
move them side by side.

00:07:09.500 --> 00:07:17.160
And so the boxes sort of look like this figure when they arrive to collide, and then in groups,

00:07:17.160 --> 00:07:18.739
they get sent to posdodge.

00:07:18.739 --> 00:07:22.559
So one will go, and then the next will go.

00:07:22.559 --> 00:07:26.959
And posdodge is the one that moves them side to side.

00:07:26.959 --> 00:07:28.200
So that's helpful.

00:07:28.200 --> 00:07:32.600
But now I want to see, OK, what's wrong with the variable width boxes that's making this

00:07:32.600 --> 00:07:34.399
not happen?

00:07:34.399 --> 00:07:38.239
I want to explore what these functions are actually doing and look at what data they

00:07:38.239 --> 00:07:41.760
see so I can try to get more insight into this.

00:07:41.760 --> 00:07:49.000
So I'm very regretful that I wrote R code for many years without using debug or trace

00:07:49.160 --> 00:07:54.320
or a lot of the really helpful tools for debugging that are built into R.

00:07:54.320 --> 00:07:57.260
So debug is one that I'll give an example of right now.

00:07:57.260 --> 00:08:02.079
And I use it all the time now because it lets you enter into the function that you're interested

00:08:02.079 --> 00:08:07.799
in and step through it and see all of the data that it's passed and see all of the transformations

00:08:07.799 --> 00:08:14.679
that it does as if you were in a regular R console.

00:08:14.679 --> 00:08:19.640
So through calling debug on the collide function, I can enter into collide.

00:08:19.640 --> 00:08:24.079
And that's what this message here is saying, debugging in collide.

00:08:24.079 --> 00:08:29.239
And I can then view the data that's being passed to the data argument of collide.

00:08:29.239 --> 00:08:33.239
So this is roughly what the data looks like for a standard box plot when all the boxes

00:08:33.239 --> 00:08:35.000
are the same size.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:39.260
The data, I removed some columns to simplify it.

00:08:39.260 --> 00:08:45.380
But there's basically one row per box that gives information about what X position it's

00:08:45.380 --> 00:08:51.960
centered at, the start and end points of the boxes horizontally, the X min and X max.

00:08:51.960 --> 00:08:55.700
And then in the data that I removed, there's also the Y position, the color and so forth.

00:08:55.700 --> 00:08:59.859
So if you had just an empty plot, this would be all the information that you would need

00:08:59.859 --> 00:09:04.900
to draw boxes on a box plot.

00:09:04.900 --> 00:09:07.679
Now we go back to my first point of isolating the problem.

00:09:07.679 --> 00:09:11.419
Because we know that this bug happens when the boxes have variable widths, but not when

00:09:11.419 --> 00:09:13.640
they have uniform widths.

00:09:13.640 --> 00:09:18.260
So I, using this debugging tool, look at the data for both cases.

00:09:18.260 --> 00:09:24.580
And I can see that for the uniform width boxes, the X min and X max for two boxes at the same

00:09:24.580 --> 00:09:26.080
position are the same.

00:09:26.080 --> 00:09:27.080
Which makes sense.

00:09:27.080 --> 00:09:28.080
They're the same size.

00:09:28.080 --> 00:09:32.820
So they're going to extend the same amount around the place where they're centered.

00:09:32.820 --> 00:09:35.299
And for the variable width boxes, they're different.

00:09:35.299 --> 00:09:38.340
Which also makes sense, because, again, they're different sizes.

00:09:38.340 --> 00:09:44.640
So they're going to extend farther or less far around where they're centered.

00:09:44.640 --> 00:09:48.880
So by comparing these data sets and viewing the code, I'm able to find the source of the

00:09:48.880 --> 00:09:50.299
bug.

00:09:50.299 --> 00:09:57.080
Because one of the things that Collide does is, again, send these groups of boxes to posdodge

00:09:57.080 --> 00:09:58.280
to be dodged.

00:09:58.280 --> 00:10:01.780
And it is doing this on the basis of their X min value.

00:10:01.780 --> 00:10:06.960
So it treats all boxes that have the same X min as being at the same position.

00:10:06.960 --> 00:10:10.479
And so then they get sent to posdodge, and they get moved from one another.

00:10:10.479 --> 00:10:15.280
But these variable width boxes don't have the same X min, so Collide doesn't realize

00:10:15.280 --> 00:10:19.580
that they occupy the same position.

00:10:19.580 --> 00:10:21.799
So now we know what the problem is.

00:10:21.799 --> 00:10:23.880
But fixing it is a whole other kettle of fish.

00:10:23.880 --> 00:10:27.520
And it may or may not be obvious, once you've found the source of the bug, what the fix

00:10:27.520 --> 00:10:29.000
ought to be.

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:33.619
So depending on what it is, you may just have to get in there and start changing things.

00:10:33.619 --> 00:10:38.380
I made a lot of minor changes to the code and saved them with commit messages like,

00:10:38.380 --> 00:10:43.179
this doesn't fix position dodge, but it might be in the right direction, before I ever got

00:10:43.179 --> 00:10:45.419
to anything that was even a plausible solution.

00:10:45.419 --> 00:10:52.280
These are real commit messages from my git ref log that I dug up to put on this slide.

00:10:52.280 --> 00:10:57.340
And so I would go in there, make changes, run the reprex again, and see if anything

00:10:57.400 --> 00:11:03.039
was different or if somehow I had fixed the problem.

00:11:03.039 --> 00:11:08.960
Since the main source of the problem was that Collide was treating these boxes with different

00:11:08.960 --> 00:11:13.900
X mins as not being at the same position, my first thinking was, well, could it use

00:11:13.900 --> 00:11:15.619
their X position instead?

00:11:15.619 --> 00:11:20.679
Because we have X as a column in the data, so maybe we can just swap that out and everything

00:11:20.679 --> 00:11:23.260
will be great.

00:11:23.260 --> 00:11:25.059
So that's roughly what I did here.

00:11:25.059 --> 00:11:29.900
And at first glance, it sort of works, but there's something wrong with this plot that

00:11:29.900 --> 00:11:35.179
maybe some of you with sharp eyes are spotting, and that's that the boxes are not in the right

00:11:35.179 --> 00:11:36.179
order.

00:11:36.179 --> 00:11:40.419
We have pink, then blue, then blue, then pink, then blue, then pink.

00:11:40.419 --> 00:11:43.419
So that's weird and not great.

00:11:43.419 --> 00:11:47.900
And then there are some other problems that are not visible in that plot, but came up

00:11:47.900 --> 00:11:53.619
in other investigations, that this doesn't work for continuous X axes, it only works

00:11:53.780 --> 00:11:56.419
for categorical ones for some reason.

00:11:56.419 --> 00:12:02.780
And then there's this problem where the boxes are actually not being, the approach to scaling

00:12:02.780 --> 00:12:05.039
the boxes is not accurate.

00:12:05.039 --> 00:12:10.460
So when the boxes get moved side to side, they need to be shrunk down in order to fit.

00:12:10.460 --> 00:12:15.659
And POSDodge is getting them in groups and scaling them by however many are in the group.

00:12:15.659 --> 00:12:19.619
So if it gets three boxes, it'll shrink it down so that the three can fit side by side.

00:12:19.619 --> 00:12:23.219
If it gets one, then it may not need to really scale it down.

00:12:23.219 --> 00:12:27.260
And so you could end up in a situation where these variable widths that are supposed to

00:12:27.260 --> 00:12:33.520
convey meaning in the plot are not really accurate at all.

00:12:33.520 --> 00:12:36.739
So this is a major problem.

00:12:36.739 --> 00:12:40.760
And one lesson here is that sometimes in trying to fix a bug, you'll end up introducing way

00:12:40.760 --> 00:12:42.960
worse bugs in the process.

00:12:42.960 --> 00:12:47.140
So that's why it's important to test many different scenarios.

00:12:47.140 --> 00:12:50.780
Isolating the problem helped me figure out the cause, but a solution needs to take into

00:12:50.780 --> 00:12:56.099
account the real world complexity of how the code is used in lots of different scenarios,

00:12:56.099 --> 00:12:57.700
lots of different types of data.

00:12:57.700 --> 00:13:03.460
Fortunately, ggplot2 has a lot of automated tests that can alert me if something that

00:13:03.460 --> 00:13:07.000
I'm changing causes unexpected changes elsewhere.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:11.799
And as I worked on different possible solutions, I also made sure to add more tests to make

00:13:11.799 --> 00:13:17.859
sure that things that I fixed didn't then get unfixed accidentally.

00:13:17.859 --> 00:13:22.380
So I then from here kind of rewrote this dodging algorithm so that it could see all

00:13:22.380 --> 00:13:26.859
the data at once instead of getting these groups of boxes separately.

00:13:26.859 --> 00:13:30.859
That way, it could scale all the boxes by the same amount and be consistent in that

00:13:30.859 --> 00:13:31.859
way.

00:13:31.859 --> 00:13:35.059
And I made some other tweaks that allowed it to work with continuous x-axes.

00:13:35.059 --> 00:13:37.820
And with these new changes, things are looking pretty good.

00:13:37.820 --> 00:13:39.780
The original issue was fixed.

00:13:39.780 --> 00:13:46.020
We have box plots that work with both continuous and categorical x-axes.

00:13:46.020 --> 00:13:50.179
And then once you have something that's working for this original example, it's worth seeing

00:13:50.179 --> 00:13:54.900
if there are ways that you can generalize it to other situations.

00:13:54.900 --> 00:14:00.260
In reviewing my work on this box plot algorithm, Hadley pointed out that with a few minor tweaks,

00:14:00.260 --> 00:14:06.099
we could generalize the algorithm to handle not just boxes, but also bars and arbitrary

00:14:06.099 --> 00:14:07.099
rectangles.

00:14:07.099 --> 00:14:13.099
And I realized that if we did this, we could solve or at least improve three other existing

00:14:13.099 --> 00:14:14.099
open issues.

00:14:14.179 --> 00:14:18.059
So we could really kind of kill a bunch of birds with one stone with this, or feed a

00:14:18.059 --> 00:14:21.260
bunch of birds with one scone.

00:14:21.260 --> 00:14:23.380
So we did this.

00:14:23.380 --> 00:14:27.460
The main thing that needed to be changed in order for the dodging algorithm to work with

00:14:27.460 --> 00:14:33.500
arbitrary rectangles is that this approach where we're looking for the x position is

00:14:33.500 --> 00:14:35.940
not really going to work anymore.

00:14:35.940 --> 00:14:41.659
Boxes and bars would be centered around the same x, but for rectangles, you could have

00:14:41.659 --> 00:14:46.900
overlapping rectangles like this one in the bottom left plot here that aren't centered

00:14:46.900 --> 00:14:52.059
at the same position, but still overlap and would need to be moved from one another.

00:14:52.059 --> 00:14:58.700
So rather than basing my determination of what boxes overlap on their x position, I

00:14:58.700 --> 00:15:05.599
wrote a for loop that compares the starting point of one box or rectangle with the ending

00:15:05.599 --> 00:15:11.219
point of the previous one so that it can check and see if there's overlap in that way.

00:15:11.219 --> 00:15:16.539
And I should say that Hadley had suggested this for loop approach from the very beginning

00:15:16.539 --> 00:15:21.619
of my work on this pull request, and for some reason, I repeatedly ignored his suggestion,

00:15:21.619 --> 00:15:25.059
which in retrospect was extremely foolish.

00:15:25.059 --> 00:15:30.140
So another takeaway of this for me has been that if Hadley tells me I should write a for

00:15:30.140 --> 00:15:34.739
loop, I probably should write a for loop.

00:15:34.739 --> 00:15:42.780
But soon we had an algorithm that was working well for boxes, bars, arbitrary rectangles,

00:15:42.780 --> 00:15:48.780
and from here, it was sort of unclear, like, when do we stop?

00:15:48.780 --> 00:15:53.179
Some bugs require only simple fixes, but for more complicated ones, it can be hard to know

00:15:53.179 --> 00:15:55.979
when you're really done.

00:15:55.979 --> 00:16:01.820
This new dodging function seemed to be performing well, so again, we want to be testing a representative

00:16:01.820 --> 00:16:07.099
variety of different cases to ensure that it is, in fact, working before we stop.

00:16:07.099 --> 00:16:09.299
That's kind of at a minimum.

00:16:09.299 --> 00:16:13.659
But once it works, there still might be more that one could do to improve it, so you need

00:16:13.659 --> 00:16:20.059
to weigh the work that it would take to make it way, way, way better or a little bit better

00:16:20.059 --> 00:16:29.739
to how important it really is to make the thing that much better.

00:16:29.739 --> 00:16:33.979
With this dodging algorithm, I had started to wonder whether it could, in fact, completely

00:16:33.979 --> 00:16:37.020
replace the original position dodge.

00:16:37.020 --> 00:16:38.820
I was really hoping that it would.

00:16:38.820 --> 00:16:42.780
It would have been really personally satisfying to kind of wrap everything up with a nice

00:16:42.780 --> 00:16:49.500
neat little bow and be able to just completely replace the old position algorithm with one

00:16:49.500 --> 00:16:52.099
that could handle a few more situations.

00:16:52.099 --> 00:16:57.739
But alas, when I tried this out, I found that it still didn't work for violin plots and

00:16:57.739 --> 00:17:01.219
dot plots, which also sometimes get dodged in ggplot.

00:17:01.219 --> 00:17:08.579
So violins, which look like this on the left, sorry, Hillary, just become slanty lines with

00:17:08.579 --> 00:17:12.140
position dodge, too.

00:17:12.140 --> 00:17:16.180
So after weeks of work, we decided to just wrap this up and call it good enough.

00:17:16.180 --> 00:17:21.099
We solved the original problem and many others besides, and while it would have felt satisfying

00:17:21.099 --> 00:17:25.819
to come up with one comprehensive dodging algorithm that could do everything, we figured

00:17:25.900 --> 00:17:29.380
that we could always come back and improve things later and it just wasn't worth the

00:17:29.380 --> 00:17:35.900
additional effort that it would take to make it completely, completely perfect.

00:17:35.900 --> 00:17:40.859
So we ended with a second dodging algorithm, position dodge 2, which is similar but slightly

00:17:40.859 --> 00:17:47.060
different to position dodge but can do some things that position dodge can't.

00:17:47.060 --> 00:17:51.540
Now in telling the story of this pull request, I really smoothed over a lot of the finer

00:17:51.540 --> 00:17:56.579
details and the pain and suffering that went into getting something that actually worked

00:17:56.579 --> 00:18:02.060
in the end, but if you want to see more of the finer details of discussion, you're welcome

00:18:02.060 --> 00:18:03.500
to read this.

00:18:03.500 --> 00:18:10.900
I don't know why you would want to, but hopefully you just get some nice plots at the end.

00:18:10.900 --> 00:18:15.140
And though I found this bug pretty challenging at the time, it's really helped me understand

00:18:15.140 --> 00:18:19.979
and fix other bugs that I've encountered by taking the strategy of isolating the problem

00:18:19.979 --> 00:18:25.380
with simple, clear examples, following the trails of the data through the code to find

00:18:25.380 --> 00:18:31.300
the problem, messing around, experimenting, breaking things and seeing what happens, then

00:18:31.300 --> 00:18:36.859
testing any fix in many different scenarios, and then when it makes sense for the problem

00:18:36.859 --> 00:18:44.859
to generalize those fixes to handle a variety of different possible cases, but always keeping

00:18:44.859 --> 00:18:51.339
in mind when the marginal rate of return is too small to be worth it.

00:18:51.339 --> 00:18:56.540
So I'd like to thank GitHub user mcall who originally reported this bug, which I don't

00:18:56.540 --> 00:18:59.420
know if there's any chance this person is here at the conference, but if so, I would

00:18:59.420 --> 00:19:05.900
love to meet you, and Hadley for reviewing the pull request and folks for giving me feedback

00:19:05.900 --> 00:19:06.900
on this talk.

00:19:06.900 --> 00:19:07.900
Thank you.

00:19:08.060 --> 00:19:09.060
Thank you.

00:19:20.140 --> 00:19:29.979
We have time for one question while we get Amelia up here.

00:19:30.020 --> 00:19:34.540
Don't ask me why the violin plots have become slanty lines, because I don't really know.

00:19:34.540 --> 00:19:53.579
The question was, how long did this take from start to finish?

00:19:53.579 --> 00:19:59.060
Sorry, let me hand this over.

00:19:59.060 --> 00:20:03.099
It was I think about three weeks.

00:20:03.099 --> 00:20:08.780
I think about three weeks, and I worked on a few other things at the time, but it was

00:20:08.780 --> 00:20:13.579
a major presence in my life for about three weeks, I think.

00:20:13.579 --> 00:20:14.579
I don't know.

00:20:14.579 --> 00:20:17.180
I could look at the pull request to be sure, but that sounds about right.

